    {
      "kind": "content",
      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "discussion",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Discussion",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "Use a node with an "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scncamera"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " instance assigned to its "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnnode/1407976-camera"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " property to view a scene. The node provides the position and direction of a virtual camera, and the camera object provides rendering parameters such as field of view and focus."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "For debugging lights and shadows, you can also designate a spotlight (an "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnlight"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " object whose "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnlight/1522919-type"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " property is "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnlighttypespot"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ") as a point of view. In this case, the light’s "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnlight/1522797-spotinnerangle"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " property determines the field of view, and its "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnlight/1522630-znear"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " and "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnlight/1522845-zfar"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " properties determine the near and far extents of the region that is visible onscreen (also known as the "
            },
            {
              "type": "emphasis",
              "inlineContent": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "text": "viewing frustum"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ")."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "In either case, the direction of view is along the negative z-axis of the node’s local coordinate space."
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
